### Footnotes

<span id="fn_713"></span>[233:1](vp068.htm#fr_713.md) It might be doubted
whether the text meant 180 in each hemisphere or in both, but the sense
is sufficiently clear in the Váyu, &c., and the number of Mańd́alas
travelled in the year is 360: the Mańd́alas, 'circles' or 'degrees,'
being in fact the sun's diurnal revolutions, and their numbers
corresponding with the days of the solar year; as in the Bhavishya P.
'The horses of the sun travel twice 180 degrees in a year, internal and
external (to the equator), in the order of the days.'

<span id="fn_714"></span>[234:2](vp068.htm#fr_714.md) A similar enumeration
of the attendants upon the sun's car occurs in the Váyu, &c. For
Yakshas, the generic term there employed is Grámańís, but the
individuals are the same. The Kúrma and Bhavishya refer the twelve
Ádityas to different months:--

